<div class="wrap">
  <div class="eyebrow">Community research · NC · Public data</div>
  <h1>Mapping ICE enforcement risk<br>from Census data</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">How we built a vulnerability model for Wake and Mecklenburg counties using publicly available ACS estimates, Census self-response rates, and community-reported sightings — and how to replicate it anywhere.</p>

  <div class="section-label">Methodology — 3 steps</div>
  <div class="method-grid">
    <div class="mc"><div class="mc-n">Step 1</div><div class="mc-t">Build the dataset</div><div class="mc-b">Download ACS B05001 (citizenship by nativity × Hispanic/Latino) and 2020 Census self-response rates per tract. Merge on GEOID. Filter to your county.</div></div>
    <div class="mc"><div class="mc-n">Step 2 — Mecklenburg</div><div class="mc-t">Dual-threshold filter</div><div class="mc-b">Flag tracts where <em>both</em> conditions are true: at-risk pop above 75th percentile <em>and</em> Census response rate below 55%. These are your Group A hotspots.</div></div>
    <div class="mc"><div class="mc-n">Step 3 — Wake</div><div class="mc-t">Vulnerability score</div><div class="mc-b">Where dual-threshold returns nothing (risk is diffuse), compute a score per tract and rank. No hard cutoff needed — top 10 captures the upper tier.</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula">
    <span class="label">Vulnerability score</span> = (% at-risk) × (1 − Census response rate)
    <div class="eg">Example: Tract 535.17 → 0.363 × (1 − 0.662) = <span>0.1227</span> &nbsp;·&nbsp; Tract 38.08 → 0.806 × (1 − 0.432) = <span>0.458</span> (Mecklenburg scale)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label" style="margin-top:20px">Choropleth maps — hover tracts for detail</div>
  <div class="maps-row">
    <div class="map-card" style="position:relative">
      <div class="map-head">Mecklenburg County</div>
      <div class="map-sub">Group A hotspots — dual threshold: at-risk &gt;75th pct + response &lt;55%</div>
      <div id="meck-tt" class="tooltip"></div>
      <svg class="choropleth" viewBox="0 0 300 260" id="meck-svg"></svg>
      <div class="legend-row">
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#8b1515"></div>80%+ at-risk</div>
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#6b1212"></div>55–80%</div>
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#4a1010"></div>43–55%</div>
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#1a2e3a"></div>Low risk</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="map-card" style="position:relative">
      <div class="map-head">Wake County</div>
      <div class="map-sub">Top 10 by vulnerability score — score = %at-risk × (1 − response rate)</div>
      <div id="wake-tt" class="tooltip"></div>
      <svg class="choropleth" viewBox="0 0 300 260" id="wake-svg"></svg>
      <div class="legend-row">
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#1a4a78"></div>Score &gt;0.10</div>
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#133860"></div>0.07–0.10</div>
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#0d2848"></div>0.05–0.07</div>
        <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-swatch" style="background:#1a2e3a"></div>Not ranked</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">Key numbers</div>
  <div class="stats-grid">
    <div class="sc"><div class="sc-val red">80.6%</div><div class="sc-lbl">Peak at-risk population<br>Mecklenburg tract 38.08</div></div>
    <div class="sc"><div class="sc-val red">43.2%</div><div class="sc-lbl">Census response rate<br>tract 38.08 — lowest found</div></div>
    <div class="sc"><div class="sc-val blue">0.1227</div><div class="sc-lbl">Top Wake score<br>tract 535.17</div></div>
    <div class="sc"><div class="sc-val teal">58%</div><div class="sc-lbl">Threshold where tracts<br>consistently appear in sightings</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">How to select polygons — step by step</div>
  <div class="howto-grid">
    <div class="hc">
      <div class="hc-t"><div class="step-num">1</div>Get the ACS data</div>
      <div class="hc-b">Go to <span class="code">data.census.gov</span> → search table <span class="code">B05001</span>. Filter by: Geography → Census Tracts → North Carolina → your county. Download as CSV. This gives you non-citizen count per tract.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="hc">
      <div class="hc-t"><div class="step-num">2</div>Get self-response rates</div>
      <div class="hc-b">Go to <span class="code">data.census.gov</span> → search table <span class="code">TSRR001</span>. Same geography filter. Column <span class="code">TSRR001_008</span> = Final Total Self-Response Rate. Download and merge on the tract GEOID.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="hc">
      <div class="hc-t"><div class="step-num">3</div>Calculate % at-risk</div>
      <div class="hc-b">Divide "Not a U.S. citizen" (Hispanic/Latino) by total tract population. This is your <span class="code">Pct_At_Risk</span>. The 75th percentile cutoff for Mecklenburg was ~43%; any tract above 43% AND with response &lt;55% = Group A.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="hc">
      <div class="hc-t"><div class="step-num">4</div>Select the polygons</div>
      <div class="hc-b">Open <span class="code">data.census.gov</span> → Maps tab. Layer: Census Tracts. Click a tract to see its GEOID. Or use <span class="code">TIGER/Line shapefiles</span> (Census website) in QGIS/ArcGIS — filter by your ranked tract list and export as GeoJSON for any mapping tool.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">What this enables</div>
  <div class="method-grid" style="margin-bottom:24px">
    <div class="mc"><div class="mc-t">Community outreach</div><div class="mc-b">Know-your-rights sessions, legal clinic staffing, and rapid-response networks can be prioritized to the exact tracts with highest combined exposure.</div></div>
    <div class="mc"><div class="mc-t">Pattern insight</div><div class="mc-b">Reported enforcement events trace the outer boundaries of high-risk tracts. At-risk population above ~58% consistently correlates with community sighting reports.</div></div>
    <div class="mc"><div class="mc-t">Replicable anywhere</div><div class="mc-b">Every county in the US has ACS B05001 and TSRR001 data. This exact methodology can be applied to any county — just swap the FIPS code in the Census download filter.</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="disclaimer">All data from publicly available sources: ACS 5-Year Estimates (B05001), 2020 Census self-response rates (TSRR001), and community-reported sighting records. Polygon geometries are schematic approximations based on known tract centroids — not TIGER/Line boundaries. This study does not guarantee safety and is intended solely to inform community protection efforts. Small sample sizes and limited sighting duration may affect results.</div>
</div>

